data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Specialized assertions — clear failure messages
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in "all match" assertion, IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "expected 3 but found N" on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(...)` | Says "value is null" instead of generic failure |

For the admin check specifically, if you just want to verify an admin exists:

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
```

Or if you need to inspect the admin further, use `ContainsSingle` when the whole list should have exactly one element:

```csharp
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);
```

The general rule: **prefer the most specific assertion available** — you get descriptive failure messages for free.
